    <title>Combined summary - Meta suggestions for this block size debate</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T22:07:32.172904+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-June/008448.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In a Bitcoin-development mailing list, members discussed the ongoing block size debate and the need for a summary of positions and arguments. Mats Henricson expressed frustration with people rehashing the same arguments without reading previous discussions or offering alternatives. Gabe Appleton offered to help create a wiki page to condense the information if someone else had permission to create it. Ethan Heilman agreed that a summary would be helpful, as he did not have time to read all the emails generated by the debate. The conversation also touched on issues such as testnet4 using 8mb blocks, bitcoin XT's role in the scheme of things, and the need for a git repo to avoid exclusive-by-default wiki policies. Pindar Wong provided a GitHub link, but Appleton requested they use the original forked version made by Heilman.The email suggests that a few days from then, the project should be posted to /r/Bitcoin to get more public comments on it. Mats urged posters to read up on all the information before rehashing what others have already said and to suggest helpful alternatives rather than just criticizing. Argument 6 has been merged with Argument 4, and a full Argument 2 has been pushed while Argument 5 is not yet defined. It is suggested that Argument 6 may be merged with Argument 4 if necessary. The project can be found at https://github.com/EthanHeilman/BlockSizeDebate. The email chain focuses on finding ways to streamline the ongoing block size debate in Bitcoin by creating a wiki page and a git repo to make the information more accessible and easier to understand. The discussion also touches upon the need to create a wiki page to condense information about the debate and avoid rehashing old arguments.</summary>
